bads <- which(ADSL$BLD_EOSINOPHIL<0)

2 Multiple Imputation for Missing Values

2.1 Imputation of ‘MRC’ and ‘FEV1’

  • This code selects specific columns from a dataset for imputation and performs the imputation using the MICE package.
  • It then creates five complete datasets with imputed values, merges each with the original dataset, and appends them to form a combined dataset.
  • Finally, it combines all the imputed datasets into one large dataframe for further analysis.
# Select only the relevant columns for imputation
variables_to_impute <- c('MRC', 'FEV1', 'LAMA_', 'SAMA_', 'LABA_', 'ICS_', 'SABA_', 'AGE_COPD_DX', 'GENDER', 'HOSPFU', 'CNSR','SMOKE_STATUS')

# Subset the dataset to include only these columns
ADSL_subset <- ADSL[, variables_to_impute]

# Impute missing values using MICE
imputed_data <- mice(ADSL_subset, m = 5, method = 'pmm', maxit = 10, seed = 500)

  # Replace the old variables with the imputed values
  adsl_imputed <- ADSL
  adsl_imputed[variables_to_impute] <- completed_data
  
  # Add a column for the imputation number
  adsl_imputed$imputation_number <- i
  
  # Add the completed dataset to the list
  completed_datasets[[i]] <- adsl_imputed
}

2.7 Generating the Regression Model to Impute Additional Missing Variables

  • This code fits linear regression models to predict the missing values for variables such as BMI, FEV/FVC ratio, Blood Eosinophil count, and FVC, using a wide range of predictors including demographics, comorbidities, and treatments.

  • Each model uses the same set of predictors to estimate the corresponding outcome variable from the combined dataset.

  • this imputation is for FEV1/FVC, FVC, Blood Eosinophil, BMI, IMD_5

### ------ BMI Imputation -----------------
# Create the formula dynamically for BMI
formula1 <- as.formula(paste("BMI ~", paste(Var_List_Reg_imputation, collapse = " + ")))

# Fit linear regression models for BMI
model_BMI <- lm(formula1, data = combined_df_MI1)

#replace the missing BMI with predicted BMI
combined_df_BMI <- combined_df_MI1 %>%
  mutate(
    BMI = ifelse(is.na(BMI), pmax(predict(model_BMI, newdata = combined_df_MI1), 0), BMI)
  )


### ------ FEV_FVC_RATIO Imputation -----------------
# Create the formula dynamically
formula2 <- as.formula(paste("FEV_FVC_RATIO ~", paste(c(Var_List_Reg_imputation,"BMI"), collapse = " + ")))

# Fit the model
model_FEV_FVC_RATIO <- lm(formula2, data = combined_df_BMI)


#replace the missing FEV_FVC_RATIO with predicted FEV_FVC_RATIO

combined_df_FEV_FVC <- combined_df_BMI %>%
  mutate(
    FEV_FVC_RATIO = ifelse(
      is.na(FEV_FVC_RATIO),
      pmin(pmax(predict(model_FEV_FVC_RATIO, newdata = combined_df_BMI), 0), 0.7), # Ensure the prediction is between 0 and 0.7
      FEV_FVC_RATIO
    )
  )
### ------ BLD_EOSINOPHIL Imputation -----------------

2.8 Function to extract model summary and return a gt table

# Function to extract model summary and return a gt table
extract_model_summary_gt <- function(model, title) {
  # Check if the input is a valid model
  if (class(model) != "lm") {
    stop("The input must be a linear model of class 'lm'.")
  }
  
  # Get the summary of the model
  model_summary <- summary(model)
  
  # Extract the desired statistics
  residual_standard_error <- model_summary$sigma
  r_squared <- model_summary$r.squared
  adjusted_r_squared <- model_summary$adj.r.squared
  f_statistic <- model_summary$fstatistic[1]
  f_statistic_df1 <- model_summary$fstatistic[2]
  f_statistic_df2 <- model_summary$fstatistic[3]
  p_value <- pf(f_statistic, f_statistic_df1, f_statistic_df2, lower.tail = FALSE)
  
  # Create a data frame for the results
  results_df <- data.frame(
    Statistic = c("Residual Standard Error", "Multiple R-squared", 
                  "Adjusted R-squared", "F-statistic", "DF1", "DF2", "P-value"),
    Value = c(residual_standard_error, r_squared, adjusted_r_squared, 
              f_statistic, f_statistic_df1, f_statistic_df2, p_value)
  )
  
  # Create a gt table
  results_gt <- gt(results_df) %>%
    tab_header(title = paste("Model Summary Statistics for", title)) %>%
    fmt_number(columns = c(Value), decimals = 4) %>%
    cols_label(Statistic = "Statistic", Value = "Value")
  
  return(results_gt)
}

2.12 Replace outlier BMIs with modified zscore lower and upper bound

  • create combined_df from combined_df_MI
combined_df<-combined_df_MI
 
 # Calculate the Median and MAD (Median Absolute Deviation) of the BMI column
median_bmi <- median(combined_df$BMI, na.rm = TRUE)
mad_bmi <- mad(combined_df$BMI, constant = 0.6745, na.rm = TRUE)
# Calculate the modified Z-score for each BMI value
combined_df$modified_zscore <- 0.6745 * (combined_df$BMI - median_bmi) / mad_bmi

# Define the threshold for outlier detection (commonly 3.5)
threshold <- 3.5
 

# Replace outliers with the upper or lower bounds (median ± threshold * MAD)
combined_df$BMI <- ifelse(combined_df$modified_zscore > threshold, 
                 median_bmi + threshold * mad_bmi, 
                 ifelse(combined_df$modified_zscore < -threshold, 
                        median_bmi - threshold * mad_bmi, 
                        combined_df$BMI))
summary(combined_df$BMI)

3 Developing Survival Models with GLMNET Regularization by RegionID

  • This code develops 10 survival models using Lasso-penalized Cox regression, with each model trained on data from 9 geographical regions, while the remaining region is left out for testing.
  • For each region, the code creates the design matrix and response variable, fits the Lasso model, performs cross-validation to find the best lambda, and stores the model results.
  • The coefficients from each model are then combined into a single dataframe for comparison across all regions.
# Loop over 10 different Regions
combined_bootstrap_se_df <- data.frame()
combined_cefficients <- data.frame()
 
# Initialize an empty list to store the results
Model_list <- list()
combined_cefficients <- data.frame()
i=1
for (i in 1:9) {
  set.seed(123)
  random_number <- sample(1:5, 1)
  train_indices <- combined_df$RegionID != i & combined_df$imputation_number == random_number
  test_indices  <- combined_df$RegionID == i
  traindb <- combined_df[train_indices, ]
  testdb <- combined_df[test_indices, ]
  
  missing_summary <- colSums(is.na(traindb[, c("CNSR", "HOSPFU", "msmWeight")]))
  #print(missing_summary)
  
  missing_summary <- colSums(is.na(testdb[, c("CNSR", "HOSPFU", "msmWeight")]))
  #print(missing_summary)
  dim(traindb)
  
  
  # Create the formula, pulling predictor list from Full_pred_list
  main_pred_formula <- as.formula(paste("~", paste(Full_pred_list, collapse = " + ")))
# Define the predictors variable for the training dataset
  X <- model.matrix(main_pred_formula, data = traindb)[,-1] # Remove the intercept
  
  dim(X)
  
  # Define the response variable for the training dataset
  y <- Surv(traindb$HOSPFU, traindb$CNSR)
  dim(y)
  
  # Define the weights
  MSMweights <- traindb$msmWeight
  
  # Fit the Lasso penalized Cox model
  lasso_cox_model <- glmnet(X, y, family = "cox", alpha = 1, weights = MSMweights) 
  cat("glmnet is fitted, Region Excluded: #", i, "\n")
  
  # Perform cross-validation to find the best lambda
  start_time0 <- Sys.time()
  cv_lasso_cox <- cv.glmnet(X, y, family = "cox", alpha = 1, weights = MSMweights, nfolds = 5, nlambda = 10)
  end_time0 <- Sys.time()
  
  # Calculate the time taken
  total_time0 <- end_time0 - start_time0
  print(total_time0)
  
  # Extract the best lambda value
  best_lambda <- cv_lasso_cox$lambda.min
  cat("cv lasso models is done! Region Excluded: #", i, "\n")
  
  
  #the linear predictors is fixed at the offset.
  x_new <- X
  lin_preds <- predict(lasso_cox_model, newx = x_new, s = best_lambda, type = "link")

  
  cph <- coxph(Surv(HOSPFU, CNSR)~lin_preds, data=traindb)
  bh <- basehaz(cph, centered=FALSE)
  #plot(bh$time,bh$hazard, type='l')
  
  bh365 <- bh$hazard[min(which(bh$time>=365))]
  
  bh365 <- bh$hazard[min(which(bh$time>=365))] #The first estimate of baseline hazard after T=365 is taken as the best value
  bh1825 <- bh$hazard[min(which(bh$time>=1825))] #The first estimate of baseline hazard after T=365 is taken as the best value
  
  # Store the best lambda and lasso model in the results list
  Model_list[[i]] <- list(best_lambda = best_lambda, lasso_cox_model = lasso_cox_model, bh365=bh365, bh1825=bh1825)
  
  # Extract the coefficients at the best lambda
  lasso_coefficients <- coef(cv_lasso_cox, s = best_lambda)
  
  # Convert the coefficients to a readable format (data frame)
  lasso_coefficients_df <- as.data.frame(as.matrix(lasso_coefficients))
  lasso_coefficients_df$Variable <- rownames(lasso_coefficients_df)
  colnames(lasso_coefficients_df)[1] <- "Coefficient"
  lasso_coefficients_df$Region <- i
  
  # Combine the coefficients from each region into a single dataframe
  combined_cefficients <- rbind(combined_cefficients, lasso_coefficients_df)
}

  #pi: predicted risk at time horizon (th) of interest. 
  #y: status at th of interest
  #tte: time variable
  #bh: predicted baseilne hazard at th of interest
  #th: time horizon of interest
  stat_calib_surv <- function(pi, y, tte, bh, th)
  {
    #Calibration in the large
    km <- survfit(Surv(time=tte, event=y)~1)
    obs <- 1-km$surv[min(which(km$time>=th))]
    pred <- mean(pi)
    lin <- log(-log(1-pi))
    cph <- coxph(Surv(tte, y)~lin)
    slope <- unname(coefficients(cph))
    
    c(intercept=(pred-obs), slope=slope)
  }

3.1.1 Creating the Net Benefit Function

# Modified NB_function to accept j and l
NB_function <- function(j, l) {
  nb_data <- thisdb  # Filter or modify thisdb based on j and l if necessary
  km <- survfit(Surv(HOSPFU, CNSR) ~ 1, data = nb_data)
  
  p1 <- 1 - km$surv[min(km$time[which(km$time >= 365)])]
  p5 <- 1 - km$surv[length(km$time)]
  
  res_NB <- matrix(NA, nrow = 9, ncol = 7)  # Increased column count for additional info
  colnames(res_NB) <- c("z", "NB1m", "NB1a", "NB5m", "NB5a", "Region", "Imputation_Number")
  
  for (i in 1:9) {
    z <- i / 10
    
    x <- timeROC::SeSpPPVNPV(z, T = nb_data$HOSPFU, delta = nb_data$CNSR, marker = nb_data$pi1, cause = 1, times = c(365), iid = FALSE)
    se1 <- x$TP[2]
    sp1 <- 1 - x$FP[2]
    
    x <- timeROC::SeSpPPVNPV(z, T = nb_data$HOSPFU, delta = nb_data$CNSR, marker = nb_data$pi5, cause = 1, times = c(365 * 5 - 1), iid = FALSE)
    se5 <- x$TP[2]
    sp5 <- 1 - x$FP[2]
    
    res_NB[i, ] <- c(
      z, 
      p1 * se1 - (1 - p1) * (1 - sp1) * z / (1 - z),
      p1 - (1 - p1) * z / (1 - z),
      p5 * se5 - (1 - p5) * (1 - sp5) * z / (1 - z),
      p5 - (1 - p5) * z / (1 - z),
      j,  # Include region information
      l   # Include imputation number
    )
  }
  
  return(res_NB)
}

3.2 Evaluating the Developed Models on the Test Set and Imputed Data Subset

  • This section evaluates the AUC of the models using the left-out region for each of the 10 regions, further dividing the left-out region’s data into 5 imputed subsets.
  • For each imputed subset, it calculates the AUC using bootstrapping with 200 replications, computes the original estimates, bias-corrected estimates, bias, and standard errors.
  • The results, including region and imputation details, are summarized and stored in a dataframe, which accumulates results across all regions and imputed subsets.
# Initialize an empty data frame to store all bootstrap results
bootstrap_se_df <- data.frame()

# Initialize a matrix to hold combined results for Net Benefits
combined_NB_results <- NULL
 

res <- matrix(NA, nrow=9*5*60, ncol=9)
colnames(res) <- c("RegionId", "Imputation", "Simulation",  
                   "AUC1","intercept1","slope1",
                   "AUC5","intercept5","slope5")
index <- 1

for (j in 1:9) {
   # Identify test indices for the current region (j) in the combined dataframe
  test_indices  <- combined_df$RegionID == j
  testdb <- combined_df[test_indices, ]
  
  # Extract j  lasso_cox_model
  lasso_cox_model <- Model_list[[j]]$lasso_cox_model

  # Extract the j best_lambda
  best_lambda <- Model_list[[j]]$best_lambda
  
  # Extract baseline hazard values at 1-year (bh365) and 5-year (bh1825) intervals
  bh365<-Model_list[[j]]$bh365
  bh1825<-Model_list[[j]]$bh1825
  
  cat("Region ID= ", j, "\n")
  
  x_new <- model.matrix(main_pred_formula,  data = testdb)[,-1]  # Remove the intercept

    
   
   # Generate linear predictors using the lasso Cox model and best lambda
   lin_preds <- predict(lasso_cox_model, newx = x_new, s = best_lambda, type = "link")
   
   # Calculate risk scores at 1-year and 5-year intervals
   pi1 <- 1-exp(-exp(lin_preds)*bh365)
   pi5 <- 1-exp(-exp(lin_preds)*bh1825)
   
   
   # Update the test dataset with calculated risk scores and survival probabilities
   testdb<-testdb %>% mutate(lin_pred=lin_preds,
                                      pi1=pi1,
                                      pi5=pi5) 
   
   
  for (l in 1:5)  {
    
    # Filter the test dataset for the current imputation
    cat("Imputation number ID= ", l, "\n")
    
    thisdb <- testdb %>% filter(imputation_number==l)
    
    # Add NB function here:
    result <- NB_function(j, l)
    combined_NB_results <- rbind(combined_NB_results, result)
    
    # Create a design matrix for the predictors, excluding the intercept
    
    # Number of bootstrap iterations
    n_iterations <- 60
    # Initialize an empty vector to store AUC scalar values
    auc1_vector <- c()
    auc5_vector <- c()
    
    # Loop over the number of bootstrap iterations
    for (f in 1:n_iterations) {
        res[index,1] <- j
        res[index,2] <- l
        res[index,3] <- f
          
        # Extract a bootstrap sample for the current iteration
        # Bootstrap sample with replacement (could have duplicate rows)

        thisdb_sub <-  thisdb[sample(nrow(thisdb), replace = TRUE), ]
        
        # Calculate the time-dependent ROC curves for 1-year and 5-year predictions
        roc_results <- timeROC(T = thisdb_sub$HOSPFU, delta = thisdb_sub$CNSR, marker = thisdb_sub$lin_pred
                            , cause = 1, weighting = "marginal", times = c(365, 365*5), iid = FALSE)
        
        AUC1<-as.numeric(roc_results$AUC[1])
        #message(AUC1)
        res[index,"AUC1"]<-AUC1
        AUC5<-as.numeric(roc_results$AUC[2])
        res[index,"AUC5"]<-AUC5
        # auc1_vector<-c(auc1_vector, AUC1) 
        # auc5_vector<-c(auc5_vector, AUC5) 
        # 
        #Calibration slope and intercept
        cal_results1 <- stat_calib_surv(thisdb_sub$pi1, thisdb_sub$CNSR, thisdb_sub$HOSPFU, bh365, 365)
        #message(cal_results1)
        res[index,"intercept1"]<-cal_results1[1]
        res[index,"slope1"]<-cal_results1[2]
        
        cal_results5 <- stat_calib_surv(thisdb_sub$pi5, thisdb_sub$CNSR, thisdb_sub$HOSPFU, bh1825, 1825)
        #message(cal_results1)
        res[index,"intercept5"]<-cal_results5[1]
        res[index,"slope5"]<-cal_results5[2]
        
        index <- index+1
        
        # if (f %% 20 == 0) {
        #     cat(f, "-")
        # }
    }
   
    print(paste0("region: ", j, ", imputation: ", l))
  }
    # end of imputation loop
}  #end of region loop

# Modify rubin_rule function to include REGION_LABEL
rubin_rule <- function(estimate_var, variance_var) {
  A <- sqldf(paste("SELECT RegionId, REGION_LABEL,", estimate_var, "AS x, ", variance_var, "AS y FROM x"))
  B <- sqldf("SELECT RegionId, REGION_LABEL, AVG(x) AS xbar, AVG(y) AS Vw FROM A GROUP BY RegionId, REGION_LABEL")
  C <- merge(A, B, by = c("RegionId", "REGION_LABEL"))
  D <- sqldf("SELECT RegionId, REGION_LABEL, SUM((x-xbar)*(x-xbar))/(COUNT(*)-1) AS Vb FROM C GROUP BY RegionId, REGION_LABEL")
  E <- merge(B, D, by = c("RegionId", "REGION_LABEL"))
  E$var <- E$Vw + E$Vb
  E
}

# Run Rubin's rule for each outcome variable
MA_list <- list(
  AUC1 = rubin_rule("AUC1", "vAUC1"),
  intercept1 = rubin_rule("intercept1", "vintercept1"),
  slope1 = rubin_rule("slope1", "vslope1"),
  AUC5 = rubin_rule("AUC5", "vAUC5"),
  intercept5 = rubin_rule("intercept5", "vintercept5"),
  slope5 = rubin_rule("slope5", "vslope5")
)

#pi: predicted risk at time horizon (th) of interest. 
#y: status at th of interest
#tte: time variable
#bh: predicted baseilne hazard at th of interest
#th: time horizon of interest
stat_calib_surv <- function(pi, y, tte, bh, th)
{
  #Calibration in the large
  km <- survfit(Surv(time=tte, event=y)~1)
  obs <- 1-km$surv[min(which(km$time>=th))]
  pred <- mean(pi)
  lin <- log(-log(1-pi))
  cph <- coxph(Surv(tte, y)~lin)
  slope <- unname(coefficients(cph))
  
  c(intercept=(pred-obs), slope=slope)
}

plot_calib_surv <- function(pi, y, tte, th, n_bins=10)
{
  #Sort the data
  n <- length(pi)
  o <- order(pi)
  pi <- pi[o]
  y <- y[o]
  tte <- tte[o]
  bin <- ntile(pi, 10) #TODO: can be made faster given the data are sorted
  
  out <- matrix(NA, nrow=n_bins, ncol=4)
  colnames(out) <- c("Predicted", "Observed", "CI_low", "CI_high")
  
  plot(NULL, xlim=c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1), xlab="Predicted", ylab="Observed")
 # Add the dynamic title to the plot
  title(paste("Calibration Plot at the End of", th / 365, "Year Follow-up"))
  
  lines(c(0,1),c(0,1), col='gray')
  
  for(i in 1:n_bins)
  {
    dt <- data.frame(pi=pi[which(bin==i)], y=y[which(bin==i)], tte=tte[which(bin==i)])
    km <- survfit(Surv(tte, y) ~ 1, data = dt)
    index <- min(which(km$time>=th))
    out[i,1] <- mean(dt$pi)
    out[i,2] <- 1-km$surv[index]
    out[i,3] <- 1-km$lower[index]
    out[i,4] <- 1-km$upper[index]
    
    lines(c(out[i,1],out[i,1]),c(out[i,3],out[i,4]))
  }
  
  lines(out[,1],out[,2])
}

5 Save final RDS file

# Initialize an empty dataframe to store the results
bh_df <- data.frame(time_period = integer(), hazard = numeric())

# Loop over i from 1 to 5
for (i in 1:5) {
  # Extract the hazard value for the given condition
  hazard_value <- bh$hazard[min(which(bh$time >= 365 * i))]
  
  # Append the result to the dataframe
  bh_df <- rbind(bh_df, data.frame(time_period = i, hazard = hazard_value))
  
}

# Save the resulting dataframe as an RDS file
saveRDS(bh_df, file = "bh_df.rds")
